                        <interp inst="t18400817-name-497" type="surname" value="GASHON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400817-name-497" type="given" value="MICHAEL"></interp>MICHAEL GASHON</persName>
                  </hi>. I live in Cow-cross. My daughter, Fanny Gashon, came home about seven o'clock on Saturday, the 18th of July, with her hands behind her, her pinafore on, and her frock gone—she is four years old.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18400817-name-498" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18400817-name-498" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400817-name-498" type="surname" value="CHARLTON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400817-name-498" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE CHARLTON</persName>
                  </hi>. I live in Cow Cross-street. I have known the prisoner about three months—I saw her on Saturday evening the 18th of July, at seven o'clock, or a little before—I saw Mr. Gashon's child—I saw the prisoner go and take the child's frock off, down Red Lion-alley—she took her into the privy, and shut the door—I peeped through a crack—they were there about ten minutes—they both came out together, and the child went home.</p>
               <p>
